               technique's diagnostic potential. In men, normalized peak
               relaxation rate was lower in Brody disease (n = 4) (-3.5 $\pm$
               1.3 s-1), nemaline myopathy type 6 (NEM6; n = 5) (-7.5 $\pm$ 1.0
               s-1), and myotonic dystrophy type 2 (DM2; n = 5) (-10.2 $\pm$
               2.0 s-1) compared to healthy (n = 14) (-13.7 $\pm$ 2.1 s-1; all
               P $\leq$ 0.01) and symptomatic controls (n = 9) (-13.7 $\pm$ 1.6
               s-1; all P $\leq$ 0.02). In women, NEM6 (n = 5) (-5.7 $\pm$ 2.1
               s-1) and McArdle patients (n = 4) (-6.6 $\pm$ 1.4 s-1) had lower
               relaxation rate compared to healthy (n = 10) (-11.7 $\pm$ 1.6
               s-1; both P $\leq$ 0.002) and symptomatic controls (n = 8)
               (-11.3 $\pm$ 1.8 s-1; both P $\leq$ 0.008). TMS-induced muscle
               relaxation achieved a high level of diagnostic accuracy (area
               under the curve = 0.94 (M) and 0.92 (F)) to differentiate
               symptomatic controls from myopathy patients. Muscle relaxation
               assessed using TMS has the potential to serve as a diagnostic
               tool, an in-vivo functional test to confirm the pathogenicity of
               unknown variants, an outcome measure in clinical trials, and
               monitor disease progression.",
  journal   = "Neuromuscul. Disord.",
  publisher = "Elsevier BV",
  volume    =  33,
  number    =  5,
  pages     = "396--404",
  month     =  may,
  year      =  2023,
  keywords  = "Muscle relaxation; Myopathy; Transcranial magnetic stimulation",
  copyright = "http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/",
  language  = "en"
}

